ProcedureHelp.#cdata:
Syntax: PROC CANCORR <options> ; 
    WITH variables ; 
    BY variables ; 
    FREQ variable ; 
    PARTIAL variables ; 
    VAR variables ; 
    WEIGHT variable ; 

The CANCORR procedure performs canonical correlation, partial canonical correlation, 
and canonical redundancy analysis. 

Canonical correlation is a generalization of multiple correlation for analyzing the 
relationship between two sets of variables. In multiple correlation, you examine the 
relationship between a linear combination of a set of explanatory variables, X, and 
a single response variable, Y. In canonical correlation, you examine the relationship 
between linear combinations of the set of X variables and linear combinations of a set 
of Y variables. These linear combinations are called canonical variables or canonical 
variates. Either set of variables can be considered explanatory or response variables, 
since the statistical model is symmetric in the two sets of variables. Simple and 
multiple correlation are special cases of canonical correlation in which one or both 
sets contain a single variable.

StatementHelp.#cdata:
VAR variable(s);

The VAR statement lists the variables in the first of the two sets of variables 
to be analyzed. The variables must be numeric.

Syntax: WEIGHT variable;

If you want to compute weighted product-moment correlation coefficients, specify 
the name of the weighting variable in a WEIGHT statement.

Syntax: WITH variables ;

The WITH statement lists the variables in the second set of variables to be analyzed. 
The variables must be numeric. The WITH statement is required.
